text: Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology (2021) 105:5541–5551 https://doi.org/10.1007/s00253-021-11404-w Rubrolone production by Dactylosporangium vinaceum: biosynthesis, modulation and possible biological function Sophie Moureu 1 & Thibault Caradec 1 & Xavier Trivelli 2 & Hervé Drobecq 1 & Delphine Beury 1,3 & Peggy Bouquet 1 & Segolene Caboche 1,3 & Eva Desmecht 1 & Florence Maurier 1,3 & Ghaffar Muharram 1 & Baptiste Villemagne 4 & Adrien Herledan 4 & David Hot 1,3 & Nicolas Willand 4 & Ruben Christiaan Hartkoorn 1 Received: 14 April 2021 / Revised: 3 June 2021 / Accepted: 8 June 2021 # The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer-Verlag GmbH Germany, part of Springer Nature 2021

Abstract Rare actinomycetes are likely treasure troves for bioactive natural products, and it is therefore important that we enrich our under- standing of biosynthetic potential of these relatively understudied bacteria. Dactylosporangium are a genus of such rare Actinobacteria that are known to produce a number of important antibacterial compounds, but for which there are still no fully assembled reference genomes, and where the extent of encoded biosynthetic capacity is not defined. Dactylosporangium vinaceum (NRRL B-16297) is known to readily produce a deep wine red-coloured diffusible pigment of unknown origin, and it was decided to define the chemical identity of this natural product pigment, and in parallel use whole genome sequencing and transcriptional analysis to lay a foundation for understanding the biosynthetic capacity of these bacteria. Results show that the produced pigment is made of various rubrolone conjugates, the spontaneous product of the reactive pre-rubrolone, produced by the bacterium. Genome and transcriptome analysis identified the highly expressed biosynthetic gene cluster (BGC) for pre-rubrolone. Further analysis of the fully assembled genome found it to carry 24 additional BGCs, of which the majority were poorly transcribed, confirming the encoded capacity of this bacterium to produce natural products but also illustrating the main bottleneck to exploiting this capacity. Finally, analysis of the potential environmental role of pre-rubrolone found it to react with a number of amine containing antibiotics, antimicrobial peptides and siderophores pointing to its potential role as a “minesweeper” of xenobiotic molecules in the bacterial environment. Key points (cid:129) D. vinaceum encodes many BGC, but the majority are transcriptionally silent. (cid:129) Chemical screening identifies molecules that modulate rubrolone production. (cid:129) Pre-rubrolone is efficient at binding and inactivating many natural antibiotics. Keywords : Rubrolone . Conjugation . Biosynthesis . Dactylosporangium . Silent cluster . Lille, CNRS, Inserm, CHU Lille, Institut Pasteur de Lille, UMR2014 - US41 - PLBS-Plateformes Lilloises de Biologie & Santé, F-59000 Lille, France Molecules for Living Systems, F-59000 Lille, France / Published online: 30 June 2021 Rare actinomycetes belonging to the genus Dactylosporangium are expected to have an important capacity to produce second- ary metabolites and bioactive natural products (Kim et al. 2011). The Dactylosporangium genus is an important producer of the RNA polymerase inhibitor, tiacumicin (fidaxomicin, pro- duced by D. aurantiacum) (Hochlowski et al. 1987; Theriault et al. 1987), as well as other antibiotics such as pyridomycin (Shomura et al. 1986), dactimicin (Ohba et al. 1981) and dactylocyclines (Tymiak et al. 1992) to name some. Despite this, relatively few Dactylosporangium species have been iso- lated and characterised, and to date only one contig-based ge- nome is available for D. aurantiacum NRRL B-8111. To better evaluate the natural product production potential of Dactylosporangium species, it is important to enrich this geno- mic knowledge and evaluate the encoded genetic capacity for natural product production.

D. vinaceum is a Dactylosporangium species identified in 1983 by Shomura and colleagues (Shomura et al. 1983) and was named after its abundant production of an uncharacterised deep wine red-coloured diffusible pigment. In addition to this pigment, D. vinaceum is also known to produce an aminogly- coside antibiotic named dactimicin (Shomura et al. 1983), also known as formimidoyl fortimicin. However, despite this knowledge, the chemical identity of the red wine pigment remains elusive, and in the absence of genomic data for D. vinaceum (or indeed any Dactylosporangium), the biosyn- thetic pathway of both these molecules is unknown. As D. vinaceum is an environmental (soil) bacterium, it is intrigu- ing to elucidate the potential role this red pigment may serve to increase the fitness of D. vinaceum. In the absence of this very basic data, we considered it pressing to investigate the identity of the red wine pigment and its potential function, as well to sequence and assemble the genome of D. vinaceum (a first for a Dactylosporangium species), to unveil the biosynthetic potential of this bacterium for the production of natural products. Strain, media and culture conditions

Dactylosporangium vinaceum NRRL B-16297 was ob- tained from the ARS Culture Collection (NRRL). D. vinaceum was routinely grown in filter sterilised GYM media (4 g/L of glucose, 10 g/L of malt extract and 4 g/L of yeast extract, pH 7.2 using KOH) or on GYM agar (GYM media with 15 g/L agar). For storage, log phase D. vinaceum culture was frozen in GYM media with 15% glycerol (stored at −80 °C). Routine culture of D. vinaceum commenced with a pre-culture, where 1 mL frozen bacteria stock was inoculated into 20 mL GYM media and cultured to mid-log phase, but without allowing for production of the red pigment (~4 days, 250 rpm, 28 °C). For subsequent cultures, the pre-culture was diluted 2% (v/v), and in the case of changing media, the pre- culture was first pelleted (3200×g, 6 min), washed and diluted in new media. In GYM media, the wine red pig- ment was typically produced 2–3 days after dilution from the pre-culture and was usually followed for 1 week. Additional culture media used were low nitrogen GYM (4 g/L of glucose, 1 g/L of malt extract and 0.4 g/L of yeast extract, pH 7.2 using KOH) and glucose-nitrate media (4 g/L of glucose, 1 g/L sodium nitrate, 0.001 g/L FeSO 4.7H 2O, 0.001 g/L MnCl 2.4H 2O, 0.001 g/L ZnSO4.7H2O, pH 7.2 using KOH). Monitoring natural product production by mass spectrometry

D. vinaceum cultures of interest were centrifuged (3200×g, 10 min), and supernatant was separated from the bacterial pellet. The supernatant was then mixed with acetonitrile (v/v) to al- low protein precipitation. Following centrifugation in a microtube (20,000×g, 5 min), the supernatant was directly injected on the analytical mass spectrometer for analysis. Analytical mass spectrometry (UHPLC-DAD-MS) Extract analysis by mass spectrometry was performed on a Dionex UltiMate 3000 system coupled to a LCQ Fleet™ ion trap mass spectrometer with tandem Diode Array Detector (Thermo Scientific). Sample separation was achieved using a reverse phase column Acquity UPLC peptide BEH C18 column (pore size 300 Å, particle size 1.7μm, 2.1×150mm, Waters, Milford, MA). Compound elution was realised using a gradient of mobile phase A (water, 0.1% formic acid, v/v) to mobile phase B (acetonitrile, 0.1% FA, v/v) at a flow rate of 0.4 mL/min. Compound purification by preparative HPLC

For the isolation of pre-rubrolone or rubrolone conjugates, a 1 L bacterial culture was centrifuged (7000×g, 20 min), and the supernatant was lyophilised. The dried extract was then re- suspended in water (50 mL) and mixed with an equal volume of acetonitrile (50 mL) to allow for protein precipitation (1 h). Extracts were then centrifuged again (3200×g, 10 min), and supernatant was lyophilised. This final extract was then re- suspended in water (10 mL) and purified by preparative HPLC on a PLC2020 purification system (Gilson, Middleton, WI, USA), using a reverse phase column XBridge BEH C18 OBD Prep Column (19 × 150 mm, pore size 130 Å, particle size: 5 μm, Waters, Milford, MA). Compounds were eluted on a linear gradient of water to 40% acetonitrile over 25 min (flow 20 mL/min) with com- pound detection at an absorbance of 295 and 345 nm. Compounds were collected with the in-build fraction collec- tor. Fractions of interest were verified for content and purity by analytical mass spectrometry (above), prior to lyophilisation. Compounds (dried) were solubilised into DMSO-d6 (com- pounds 1b, 3, 6, 9), CDCl3 (compound 11), or into D2O with DSS as a reference for chemical shifts (for the remaining com- pounds) and transferred into standard NMR tubes. The chem- ical shifts were referenced according to DSS (1H and 13C at 0.00 and 0.00 ppm, respectively), residual DMSO-d5 (2.50 Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2021) 105:5541–5551 Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2021) 105:5541–5551

and 39.78 ppm) or residual CHCl3 (7.26 and 77.36 ppm). NMR experiments were run at 293 K (DMSO-d6 and CDCl3) or 300 K (D2O) on a Bruker AVANCEIIIHD 600 spectrometer equipped with a cryo-1H/2H/13C/15N/19F-QCI probe. For mono-dimensional 1H experiments, 1H selective- TOCSY (80 ms mixing time (Tm)), 1H selective-NOESY (Tm =500 ms), 13C{1H}, 13C-DEPT45 and 13C-DEPT135, bi-dimensional 1H-COSY, 1H-TOCSY (Tm=60 ms), 1H- NOESY (Tm =300 ms), 1H-ROESY (Tm =400 ms), 1H-13C- HSQC, 1H-13C-HSQC-DEPT, 1H-13C-HSQC-TOCSY (Tm =60 ms), 1H-13C-HMBC (3.3, 5, 8 or 10 Hz long-range cou- pling constants) and 1H-15N-HMBC (5 or 8 Hz long-range coupling constants) were recorded. All the NMR spectra were acquired, processed and analysed with Topspin software. Genome extraction, sequencing, assembly and annotation

D. vinaceum genomic DNA was extracted from 5 mL of D. vinaceum 4 days old pre-culture. Bacteria were pelleted (4000 rpm, 10 min) and re-suspended in 400 μL SET solution (20% w/v sucrose, 50 mM EDTA, 50 mM Tris-HCl, pH 8.0), incubated with 10 mg/mL lysozyme (37 °C, 2 h) followed by 20 μL RNAse A (Invitrogen Purelink, 37 °C, 30 min) follow- ed by incubation with proteinase K (56 °C, 1 h). Samples were centrifuged and DNA extracted from the supernatant using the phenol-chloroform-isoamyl alcohol method. Following con- firmation of DNA integrity on an agarose gel, genomic DNA was sheared in a Covaris g-TUBE (Covaris, Woburn, MA, USA) to obtain 20 kb fragments. After shearing the DNA size distribution was checked on a Fragment Analyzer (Advanced Analytical Technologies, Ames, IA, USA). Two microgrammes of the sheared DNA was used to prepare a SMRTbell library with the PacBio SMRTbell Template Prep Kit 1 (Pacific Biosciences, Menlo Park, CA, USA) according to the manufacturer’s recommendations. The resulting library was size selected on a BluePippin system (Sage Science, Inc. Beverly, MA, USA) for molecules larger than 8 kb. The re- covered library was sequenced on one SMRT cell with P6/C4 chemistry and MagBeads on a PacBio RSII system (Pacific Biosciences, Menlo Park, CA, USA) at 240 min movie length. Sequencing was performed on a PacBio RSII sequencer at the Lausanne Genomic Technologies Facility, resulting in 78-fold genome coverage. D. vinaceum genome then was assembled using the HGAP version 3.0 (Chin et al. 2013) and toAmos (Treangen et al. 2011) assembly software. The circular assem- bled genome was orientated to allow start of annotation from DnaA. The genome was deposited and annotated by NCBI (access

3.0 (Chin et al. 2013) and toAmos (Treangen et al. 2011) assembly software. The circular assem- bled genome was orientated to allow start of annotation from DnaA. The genome was deposited and annotated by NCBI (accession number: CP061913). D. vinaceum biosynthetic gene clusters were detected using antiSMASH v5.0 (Blin et al. 2019).

Transcriptome analysis of D. vinaceum by RNAseq Transcriptome analysis was performed on D. vinaceum grown under different conditions by RNAseq. RNA extraction was performed using the GTC method. Briefly, 4 mL of the bac- terial culture of interest was mixed directly into 8 mL of 1.5X GTC solution (6 M guanidium thiocyanate solution, 0.15 M beta-mercaptoethanol), to instantly stabilise bacterial RNA without lysing the bacteria. The bacteria were centrifuged (3200×g, 15 min, 4 °C) and the pellet re-suspended in 900 μL of TRIzol® reagent (Thermo Fisher Scientific), transferred in a lysing matrix tube (MP Biomedicals™, lysing matrix B) and stored at −80 °C. For RNA extraction, lysing tubes were thawed and cells were disrupted by bead beating (3 × 30 s, at maximum power, FastPrep, MP Biomedicals), with 5 min on ice in-between. The matrix tubes were then centrifuged (21,000×g, 10 min, 4 °C), and the supernatant transferred to a new tube for RNA extraction following the TRIzol® reagent protocol according to manufacturer’s instructions.

Nucleic acid obtained from the TRIzol extraction was treat- ed with 2 rounds of DNase I treatment (Sigma-Aldrich) to remove residual genomic DNA, followed by rRNA depletion using Ribo-Zero rRNA removal kit (Illumina). D. vinaceum sequencing libraries were prepared using Kapa Stranded RNAseq Library Preparation Kit (Kapa Biosystems). Libraries were paired-end (2 x 75 bp) sequenced on a NextSeq500 sequencer (Illumina). All generated raw RNAseq data was deposited in NCBI (PRJNA724875). Obtained fastq files were analysed using CLC Genomic Workbench (Qiagen) to determine expression level using an- notation files obtained by WGS. D. vinaceum genomes and RNAseq data were visualised using CLC sequence viewed 8.0 (Qiagen) and Artemis 15.0.0 (Wellcome Trust Sanger insti- tute). Biosynthetic gene cluster analysis was performed using antiSMASH 5.0 (Blin et al. 2019), and clusters were com- pared using MAUVE (Darling et al. 2004). Protein sequences of interest were analysed by Blast (NCBI), SWISS-MODEL (Waterhouse et al. 2018) and Clustal Omega tool (Madeira et al. 2019). Screening for chemical modulator of rubrolone production and RNA extraction A library of 640 potential modulators of transcription was assembled based on molecules developed around research published previously (Willand et al. 2009; Flipo et al. 2011; Flipo et al. 2012a; Flipo et al. 2012b; Villemagne et al. 2014; Blondiaux et al. 2017; Prevet et al. 2019; Villemagne et al. 2020). Prior to screening, each of the 640 chemical modula- tors (2.5 μL at 10 mM) were distributed into 96-deep well plates (Masterblock® PP, 2 mL, 96-square well plates, V- bottom, Greiner Bio-one) using a BRAVO liquid handling device (Perkin Elmer). Screening D. vinaceum cultures were

prepared by pelleting and weighing a non-clumpy cell suspen- sion of D. vinaceum and re-suspending it to 20 mg of bacteria/ mL of GYM media. Five hundred microlitres of this D. vinaceum screening culture was then added to all the wells making the final chemical modulator concentration 50 μM. Plates were then covered using an Air-O-Seal Hydrophobic Gas Permeable Seal (4titude) and incubated for 4 days (28 °C, 350 rpm, multitron shaking incubator, Infors, with 96 well plate adaptor). Results on rubrolone/red pigment formation were determined visually by looking at the bottom of 96 well culture plate. For hit compounds, the modulation of rubrolone production was confirmed using 15 mL D. vinaceum screen- ing cultures in 100 mL Erlenmeyer flasks in the absence and presence of the hit modulators. To determine the impact of the hit modulator BDM44661 on D. vinaceum transcription, RNA was extracted from the 4-day cultures using the TRIzol RNA extraction method (per manufacturer’s instructions), and sub- sequent RNAseq analysis (as described above). Purification of kanamycin rubrolone conjugates For the production of kanamycin rubrolone conjugates, D. vinaceum pre-culture was washed and inoculated (10% v/v) into 500 mL of nitrate-glucose media and allowed to grow for 7 days (28 °C, 250 rpm) until the media turned brown, and mass spectrometry showed high production of pre-rubrolone in the media. At this point, 50 mg of kanamycin was added to the culture and left to react for 2 h (28 °C, 250 rpm). The culture supernatant was then treated with 50% ace- tonitrile (final concentration), the supernatant was dried by lyophilisation and pure rubrolone conjugates were purified by preparative HPLC and their structures validated by NMR (as above). Reactivity of pre-rubrolone with a panel of xenobiotic molecules

Pre-rubrolone was isolated from D. vinaceum grown in nitrate glucose media (2 L). The reactivity of purified pre-rubrolone with a panel of antibiotics and siderophores was evaluated as described previously (Cai et al. 2017). The product of the conjugation reaction was analysed by analytical UHPLC- DAD-MS as described above. Elucidation of the chemical identity of the D. vinaceum red wine pigment The red wine coloured supernatant of a 5-day-old D. vinaceum culture had a corresponding maximum absorbance peak at around 540 nm. UHPLC-DAD-MS analysis of the crude

supernatant extract (concentrated by lyophilisation) revealed a number of separate peaks with a maximum absorbance of 540 nm, with the three largest peaks having a mass of 442.3, 562.3 and 298.3 (m/z [M+H]+). Preparative HPLC-UV puri- fication of these compounds (from 1 L of D. vinaceum super- natant), and NMR analysis, identified these molecules as rubrolone A, rubrolone B and rubrolone A aglycon (Fig. 1), tropolone-based natural products previously identified as products of Streptomyces echinoruber sp. (Schuep et al. 1978) and Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033 (Yan et al. 2016). The rubrolone family of natural products have been shown by Yan and colleagues (Yan et al. 2016) to be a spontaneous product of a chemical conjugation reaction between a reactive “pre-rubrolone” with nucleophilic media components such as ammonia (rubrolone A), and other amino containing com- pounds. In line with this, further analysis of the UHPLC-MS data of the D. vinaceum supernatant also identified masses corresponding to many other amino acid conjugates of rubrolone (Table S1), including rubrolone conjugates with tryptamine, lysine and glycine that were isolated and con- firmed by NMR (supplementary NMR data: Fig. S13-16 Tables S7-8). Interestingly, for all rubrolone conjugates exam- ined (except the rubrolone A aglycon), a likely oxidised form (mass loss of 2-Da) was also detected (with a slightly longer retention time on C18 column). In the case of rubrolone A, NMR structural analysis identified this analogue to be oxidised 3-keto-fucose analogue of rubrolone (Fig. 1, supple- mentary NMR data: Fig. S13-16 Tables S7-8). As reported previously (Yan et al. 2016), diminishing the amino acid con- centration in the media (10% of original malt and yeast ex- tract) drastically decreased the formation of rub

supple- mentary NMR data: Fig. S13-16 Tables S7-8). As reported previously (Yan et al. 2016), diminishing the amino acid con- centration in the media (10% of original malt and yeast ex- tract) drastically decreased the formation of rubrolone conju- gates and instead allowed for the accumulation of the non-red (yellow coloured) D-fucose-fused-tricyclic-rubrolone precur- sor (aka pre-rubrolone) to accumulate in the media (as well as its 3-keto-fucose form) (Fig. S1).

Genome sequencing and identification of rubrolone biosynthetic gene cluster in D. vinaceum To define the biosynthetic gene cluster for rubrolone in D. vinaceum (NRRL B-16297) and, more generally, to define the encoded potential of Dactylosporangium species to pro- duce natural products, the genome was fully sequenced by PacBio and assembled to form a single circular chromosome of 11.96 Mb (with a GC content of 72.3%) (Fig. S2). The genome carried 10,777 encoded genes, 80 tRNA and 2 copies of the ribosome rRNAs. As with many Streptomyces species, the TTA codon was found to be a rare leucine codon, consti- tuting only 535/377207 (or 0.14%) of all leucine-encoding codons present in D. vinaceum, suggesting involvement in translational regulation. The assembled genome of D. vinaceum NRRL B-16297 has been deposited in the GenBank database with the accession number CP061913. The “red” peaks with associated mass spectral data are [1] rubrolone A, [1’] 3-keto- fucose rubrolone A, [2] rubrolone A aglycon, [3] rubrolone B and [3’] the oxidised 3-keto-fucose rubrolone B (based on molecular mass). c Chemical structures of the first two molecules [1] rubrolone A, [1’] 3-keto-fucose rubrolone as validated by NMR.

Genome-wide biosynthetic gene cluster identification was performed on D. vinaceum using antiSMASH v5.0 in strict mode (Blin et al. 2019), revealing 25 BGCs, including five NRPS, seven hybrid-NRPS, two PKS (Type-2 and Type-3), four terpene, two siderophore, two resorcinol, two lanthipeptide and one bacteriocin cluster (Table S2). BGC 6 was found to have strong homology to the R1128 biosynthetic gene cluster from Streptomyces sp. R1128 (Marti et al. 2000) (MIBIG: BGC0000261, 85% homology) and the rubrolone A biosynthetic gene cluster from Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033 (Yan et al. 2016) (BGC0001762, 63%), and hence the likely BGC coding for the rubrolone biosynthetic machinery in D. vinaceum. In addition to these, a further BGC highly ho- mologous to the fortimicin BGC of Micromonospora olivasterospora (Dairi et al. 1992) was identified that is likely a s s o c i a t e d t o t h e p u b l i s h e d p r o d u c t i o n o f t h e pseudodisaccharide aminoglycoside, dactimicin (Shomura et al. 1983) by D. vinaceum (Dvina_05375-495). Global transcriptome analysis D. vinaceum RNAseq To achieve rubrolone production, it is expected that its BGC is transcribed, and therefore a transcriptome analysis was per- formed on D. vinaceum growing in late log phase (when it was at the start of visible rubrolone production). This analysis showed that amongst the identified BGC, BGC 6 was the most highly expressed, in particular 31 consecutive genes from Dvina_17740 to Dvina_17890 that likely present the cluster

e v + I S E , y t i s n e t n boundary and here subcategorised as BGC 6a (Table S3/S4). Interestingly, the majority of other BGCs in D. vinaceum were either silent or very poorly transcribed, including the identi- fied dactimicin cluster (Table S3/S4). This RNAseq data indi- cated that despite the large number of BGC of D. vinaceum, transcriptional regulation appears a major barrier to mining these bacteria for their potential secondary metabolites under the tested growth conditions. Confirmation of the rubrolone biosynthetic gene cluster using a transcriptional modulator Confirming the association of BGC 6a with rubrolone biosyn- thesis is classically achieved by determining the impact of genetically inactivating the cluster on rubrolone production. In our hands however, unlike D. aurantiacum (Xiao et al. 2010; Xiao et al. 2011), we were unable to transform D. vinaceum with integrative plasmids (dam/dcm methylated and non-methylated), neither through electroporation nor con- jugation methods, making this approach not feasible. As an alternative exploratory approach, we decided to evaluate if we could screen a chemical library for molecules that would spe- cifically modulate the production of rubrolone and then define the involvement of BGC 6a. To increase the chance of finding a modulator of rubrolone biosynthesis, it was decided to screen 640 molecules that orig- inated from chemistry programmes focused on developing transcription factor modulators for M. tuberculosis.

Screening of the chemical library (50 μM) on rubrolone pro- duction by D. vinaceum in an optimised, miniaturised, medium-throughput approach led to the identification of a 5,5,5-trifluoro-1-(1-piperidyl)pentan-1-one (BDM44661, Fig. S3, S4) that prevented rubrolone formation with minimal impact on D. vinaceum growth itself. This inhibition of rubrolone production was confirmed when D. vinaceum was grown under conventional conditions in Erlenmeyer flasks (15 mL cultures) (Fig. 1). Having identified BDM44661 as a modulator of rubrolone biosynthesis, transcriptome analysis of D. vinaceum in the absence and presence of this molecule was performed. Results showed that global gene expression was unaffected by BDM44661 with only 257 genes dysregulated (Z- score>2, 110 genes upregulated, 147 genes downregulated) (Fig. 1). Of these dysregulated genes, the most impacted were the 31 expressed genes of BGC 6a that were almost complete- ly silenced (218-fold down-regulation) (Fig. 2 but also Fig. S5 and Table S4/S5). This identification of a chemical modulator Fig. 2 a Pictures of the 4-day-old D. vinaceum cultures grown in Erlenmeyer flasks in the absence and presence of 50 μM BDM44661 (transferred to 15 mL tubes for picture). The picture clearly shows the impact of BDM44661 on the production of the wine red pigment by D. vinaceum while still allowing for bacterial growth. b MA plots show- ing differential gene expression analysis of D. vinaceum transcription following exposure to 50 μM of BDM44661 (M, average gene expres- sion [1/2(log2(BDM) + log2(DMSO)], A, change in gene expression [log2(BDM44661) - log2(DMSO)]). Differentially expressed genes are colour coded according to Z-score (<2 = light grey, 2> = dark grey and of rubrolone production, coupled with transcription analysis, provided strong alternative validation of the association of BGC 6 to rubrolone production.

Comparison of D. vinaceum BGC 6 with Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033 rubrolone BGC The D. vinaceum rubrolone BGC 6a carries 31 genes (Dvina_17740 to Dvina_17890) compared to the 24 genes of the previously characterised rubrolone BGC of Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033 (Yan et al. 2016). Of these 31 genes, 23 homologues of the 24 rubrolone BGC genes of Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033 were found largely organised in the same way (Fig. 2c) (Table S6). The single gene missing in BGC 6a is a homologue of RubS4 that encodes a dTDP- glucose 4,6-dehydratase (aka rmlB) needed for the formation of the dTDP-4-keto-D-glucose rubrolone precursor (Yan et al. 2016). KIB-H033, have different roles t w o s h o r t a n n o t a t e d g e n e s a n d o r i g i n s . F i r s t l y , (Dvina_17795 and Dvina_17860) were found to be due to alternative gene annotation and are in fact present in the rubrolone BGC of Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033. These two genes are predicted to encode short polyketide cyclases simi- lar to like-sized olivetolic acid cyclase from Cannabis sativa (according to SWISS-MODEL) (Yang et al. 2016), with ho- mologues ORFs found between rubA and rubB (Fig. S7) and between rubE4 and rubE5, respectively (Fig. S8). Three other BGC 6a genes (Dvina_17835-845) are homologous to zhuF, E and D of the R1128 BGC of Streptomyces lividans (Marti et al. 2000) and encoded for subunits of an acetyl-CoA car- boxylase (Fig. 2c, Table S6). This additional in-cluster acetyl- CoA carboxylase likely allow for improved malonyl-CoA precursor production (as in the R1128 BGC (Marti et al. 2000)) and may explain the striking abundant production of rubrolone by D. vinaceum. The remaining three genes in the middle of BGC 6a (Dvina_17810-820) encode a disrupted transposase and two incomplete MaoC family dehydratases respectively that are a likely 3-ORF “scar” from a transposi- tion event (Table S6), and not involved in the rubrolone bio- synthesis (Table S5). Finally, rubN2 of Streptomyces sp. KIB- H033 genome was found to be miss-annotated with transla- tion likely starting from an alternative upstream start codon (Fig. S9), making it homologous to Dvina_17785, a predicted TetR/AcrR transcriptional repressor. This all considered, the BGC 6a is highly similar to the rubrolone BGC of Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033, with the addition of malonyl- CoA biosynthesis from R2118, with rubrolone biosynthesis likely conserved (summarised in Fig. S10).

Bioactivity of pre-rubrolone and rubrolone conjugates Rubrolone A and rubrolone B were found to have no antibac- terial activity (S. pneumoniae, S. aureus, A. baumannii, K. pneumoniae, P. aeruginosa, E. coli, E. coli ΔtolC), anti- fungal activity (C. albicans) nor any cytotoxic activity against HepG2 cells to concentrations of up to 100 μg/mL, in line with previous reports (Palleroni et al. 1978). The rubrolone analogue, isarubrolone F, has been reported to induce autoph- agy (Li et al. 2019), and indeed, we could confirm that rubrolone A mildly induced auto-phagosome numbers in RAW264.7 cells (Fig. S11), though the magnitude of the in- duction and the need for high concentrations question its rel- evance as its physiological role in D. vinaceum. The evalua- tion of the pre-rubrolone biological activity was prevented by the reactivity of pre-rubrolone with amino acids/proteins in the culture media, transforming it to red-coloured rubrolone conjugates. D. vinaceum survival in the absence of ammonia and amino acid nitrogen sources

The reactivity of pre-rubrolone with ammonia and amino acids raised the question of how D. vinaceum survived with- out such a nitrogen source. Analysis of the D. vinaceum ge- nome however revealed a likely capacity to obtain nitrogen by nitrate assimilation, namely, coding for a nitrate transporter (Dvina_49605, NarK/NasA family), a nitrate reductase (Dvina_22975, NarB-like), nitrite reductases (Dvina_49615- 20, NirB- and NirD-like) and a number of nitrate sensors (NarX-like) and regulators (NasR, NarL-like). Indeed, we found that D. vinaceum could grow in media with nitrate as sole nitrogen source, which led to abundant biosynthesis of the non-reacted pre-rubrolone in the supernatant, with no mea- surable levels of rubrolone A or B conjugates or other rubrolone conjugates. Reactivity of pre-rubrolone with xenobiotics and siderophores

The biosynthetically uncontrolled synthesis of rubrolone con- jugates (from pre-rubrolone) makes them an unlikely bioac- tive product of biosynthesis, but instead the reactive pre- rubrolone itself. This nonetheless questions which nucleophile-containing molecules in the bacteria’s natural en- vironment are intended to be captured by pre-rubrolone to provide a benefit to the bacterium and justify the energy ex- penditure of synthesising this natural product. We therefore sought to investigate if pre-rubrolone could react with natural product antibiotics. This reactivity was evaluated by mixing purified pre-rubrolone with a panel of natural xenobiotic mol- ecules and following the fate of the molecules by UHPLC- DAD-MS analysis. Here, aminoglycosides, kanamycin, amikacin and apramycin were found to react very quickly with pre-rubrolone (rapid colour change to red, particularly for kanamycin and amikacin), with near complete conversion to rubrolone-aminoglycoside conjugates (UVmax: 540 nm) as determined by mass spectrometry (Fig. S12a). The gentamicin sulphate salt tested for this reaction was a mixture of gentami- cin C1a, C1 and C2, with only rubrolone-gentamicin C1a conjugates detected by mass spectrometry. Of the gentamicin analogues, gentamicin C1a has the most accessible primary amine (nucleophile) of the three compounds, with gentamicin C1 having a secondary amine, and C2 having a sterically hindered primary amine. Streptomycin, which has no nucleo- philic primary amines, was found not to react at all with pre- rubrolone. Regarding non-aminoglycoside antibiotics tested, rubrolone-ampicillin conjugates were formed (ampicillin car- ried a primary amine), but no rubrolone conjugates could be detected for penicillin G, erythromycin nor novobiocin (Fig. S12b), all of which lack a reactive primary amine.

Kanamycin, with multiple primary amines, was found to form a number of rubrolone-kanamycin conjugates. To con- firm that the conjugation reaction can occur in D. vinaceum culture supernatant, and to confirm the structures of the con- jugates, kanamycin was added to a D. vinaceum culture pro- ducing pre-rubrolone (grown in nitrate-based media). The me- dia supernatant quickly turned from a brown to red colour, and the formation of rubrolone-kanamycin conjugates and the de- crease of pre-rubrolone were confirmed by mass spectrome- try. Two rubrolone-kanamycin conjugates were purified and their structures solved by NMR (supplementary NMR data: Fig. S13-16 Tables S7-8), confirming rubrolone-kanamycin conjugates formed by reactivity on distinct kanamycin amino group (Fig. 3). Analysis of reactivity of pre-rubrolone with peptidic anti- biotic molecules further confirmed the promiscuous nature of rubrolone conjugate formation (Fig. S12c). To this extend, pre-rubrolone reacted with the glycopeptide antibiotic vanco- mycin (carries a potential reactive amino sugar moiety), the antibacterial polycationic peptide colistin (which carries 5 po- tential reactive ornithine residues), the antimicrobial lipopeptide daptomycin (which contains a lysine and primary aniline reactive groups) and the antimicrobial peptide nisin (which carries 3 potential reactive lysine groups). Finally, it was also confirmed that pre-rubrolone could conjugate a Fig. 3 The chemical structures of the two rubrolone-kanamycin conjugates (a and b) isolated from kanamycin fed D. vinaceum cul- ture (grown on a nitrate based ni- trogen source). All molecules were isolated from culture super- natants, and structurally validated by NMR. common natural product siderophore, desferrioxamine B, used by many bacteria, that carries a terminal lysine (Fig. S12b).

Many rare actinomycetes are thought to be a storehouse of natural products but are under-explored, including Dactylosporangium species. Here, by assessing the fully as- sembled genome of D. vinaceum, it revealed that D. vinaceum indeed carried an abundant number of encoded biosynthetic gene clusters and the potential to generate a large diversity of natural products. What however became very apparent from the transcriptomic data is that despite the large potential abun- dance of BGCs, the majority are transcriptionally silent, and likely not producing associated natural products in the labora- tory conditions tested. Future attempts to awaken these BGC will be essential to fully unravel the diversity of natural prod- ucts, and bioactive molecules that can be produced by D. vinaceum. The deep red wine diffusible pigment of D. vinaceum was here found to be caused by molecules of the rubrolone family of tropolones, and their genome-encrypted biosynthesis was associated with a BGC, through homology with a known rubrolone BGC and confirmed using a chemical transcription- al modulator that repressed the transcription of the BGC. D. vinaceum rubrolone BGC was highly homologous to the previously described rubrolone BGC of Streptomyces sp. KIB- H033 (Yan et al. 2016), with the addition of malonyl-CoA biosynthesis genes that likely help the provision of PKS build- ing blocks needed for the efficient rubrolone biosynthesis. In addition, the analysis of the biosynthetic cluster organisation and the transcriptional silencing of the BGC by BDM44661 allowed for an insight into cluster transcriptional regulation. Analysis of rubrolone conjugates and precursors produced by D. vinaceum was largely in line with findings previously pub- lished for rubrolone, isatropolone and rubterolone (Palleroni et al. 1978; Schuep et al. 1978; Cai et al. 2017; Guo et al. 2017). In agreement with recent revised rubrolone glycoside biosynthesis, our analysis did identify new 3-keto-fucose- rubrolone analogues which appears to be derived from a likely intermediate in the dTDP-2-keto-antiarose to dTDP-2-keto- fucose epimerisation (Yan et al. 2020). In the absence of functioning genetic tools for the genetic manipulation of D. vinaceum, the identification of molecules to modulate rubrolone production in combination with tran- scriptome analysis proved useful to validate the association of BGC 6a with rubrolone production. The identified BDM44661 appeared to have specific activity on the transcription of BGC 6a, and this may be due to potential interaction with one of the two in cluster transcriptional regulators. As well as for valida- tion purposes, the use of chemical libraries may also serve to help activate (de-repress) other silent BGCs in D. vinaceum and serve as a tool to discovery of novel bioactive natural products, and this possibility is currently being investigated.

The genus-wide biosynthesis of rubrolones and chemically similar isarubrolones, and rubterolones by Dactylosporangium, Streptomyces and Actinomadura species (Palleroni et al. 1978; Schuep et al. 1978; Cai et al. 2017; Guo et al. 2017), supports the hypothesis that these molecules (or precursors) provide a general benefit to the producing bacteria. In all these cases, the conjugat- ed tropolones had no or very little antibacterial, antifungal or cytotoxic activity, and in our opinion, this is because these red pigments are in fact the inactivated “waste” product of the chem- ically reactive and bioactive pre-rubrolone (or pre-rubterolone or isatropolone). Indeed isatropolones have been shown to have activity against Leishmania donovani (Cai et al. 2017) through a thus far undefined mechanism. Data from this study provides two additional possible functions of pre-rubrolone. A first hy- pothesis is that secreted pre-rubrolone reacts with environmental amino-based nitrogen sources, to impede the growth of microor- ganisms that rely on this nitrogen source, while itself surviving of nitrate (notably, Streptomyces sp. KIB-H033, also carries genes for nitrate reduction). This type of function may also manifest in a symbiotic relation with for example plant species. A second hypothesis is that pre-rubrolones can act as a “mine-sweeper” of nucleophile containing natural products such as amino- glucosides or antimicrobial peptides, thus detoxifying its immediate environment. While it is self-evident that rubrolone conjugation would neutralise the activity of most antibiotics, it is challenging to validate that this is its intended function in nature. Such validation would ideally be achieved using a competing bacterium that produces an amine-containing antibiotic when grown on a solid nitrate-based medium (non-amino acid media to prevent re-rubrolone inactivation).

Overall, this work makes important steps to define the nat- ural product biosynthesis potential of Dactylosporangium species and highlights the transcriptional barriers that may be faced for exploiting natural product formation. With the use of chemical modulators, we demonstrate an alternative means of affecting BGC transcription, an approach that may be used to awaken silent BGCs in future studies. Furthermore, this work has added to the knowledgebase for rubrolone bio- synthesis, with added insight into cluster regulation. Finally, this work suggests an alternative biological function for the chemically reactive pre-rubrolones.
